<DOC><DOCNO> ZF310-730-831 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 730 831.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC User  April 24 1991 n157 p17(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EMAP Business andamp; Computer Publications (UK)1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Microsoft faces up to FTC probe. (US Federal Trade Commissioninvestigates Microsoft Corp.'s alleged monopolistic practices)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (Investigations).andO;Ticker:    MSFT.andO;Topic:     United States. Federal Trade CommissionInvestigationsGovernment RegulationMonopoliesCompetitionAntitrust LawsLegal Issues.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Microsoft has officially admitted that the US Fair Trade Commission haswidened its investigation into alleged monopolistic practices.andM;The company originally stated that the FTC investigation centred on anow-defunct 1989 agreement with IBM to limit the capabilities of Windows 3.0.andM;But the FTC has since stated it will investigate charges that Microsoft has&quot;monopolised, or attempted to monopolise, the market for operating systems,operating environments, computer software and computer peripherals for PCs&quot;.andM;The uneasy relationship between Microsoft as a developer of operating systemsand applications, and the rest of the industry is perhaps illustrated by itsalleged sneak preview of Go's PenPoint operating system as a potentialdeveloper.andP;  Microsoft has now launched an alternative to Go through PenWindows.andO;</TEXT></DOC>